se studies--from the China Investment Corporation to the funds of several Gulf states--the authors show that the forces propelling the adoption and development of sovereign wealth funds vary by country. The authors also show that many of these investment institutions have identifiable commonalities of form and function that match the core institutions of Western financial markets. The authors suggest that the international legitimacy of sovereign wealth funds is based on the degree to which their design and governance match Western expectations about investment management. Undercutting commonplace assumptions about the emerging world of the twenty-first century, the authors demonstrate that even small countries with large and globally oriented sovereign wealth funds are likely to play a significant role in international relations. Sovereign Wealth Funds considers how such financial organizations have altered not only the face of finance, but also the international geopolitical landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInvestments, ForeignvCase studies. 0aInvestments, ForeignxCase studies. 0aInvestments, Foreign. 0aSovereign wealth fundsxLaw and legislation. 0aSovereign wealth funds. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  aAsian financial crisis.  aAustralia.  aChina Investment Corporation.  aDutch disease.  aEast Asia.  aFuture Fund.  aGenerally Accepted Principles and Practices.  aGovernment Pension Fund-Global.  aGovernment of Singapore Investment Corporation.  aGulf states.  aMiddle East.  aNorway.  aSantiago Principles.  aWestern interests.  acapitalism.  acapitalist development.  adomestic politics.  aeconomic geography.  aethical policy.  afinance.  afinancial crisis.  afinancial institutions.  afinancial markets.  afinancialization.  